H&E to ST

Introduction

We have two spatial transcriptomics samples with accompanying H&E images. The goal is to predict gene expression using random forests.

Non-Spatial Random Forests

In this section, Ill create two RF models (one for each of our two images) and use them to predict THY1 expression in the other sample.

Sample 1 model

First, lets try making a model based on sample 1

Prediction

Next, well look at how the models perform when run on the opposite sample

##       Predicted
## Actual         1         2
##      1 0.8722222 0.1277778
##      2 0.8448276 0.1551724
##       Predicted
## Actual          1          2
##      1 0.97311828 0.02688172
##      2 0.96666667 0.03333333

We see that both models predict 1 (low THY1 expression) really well, but 2 (high THY1 expression) is being mis-classified frequently.

Re-running workflow with global thresholding

One possible fix could be to use global thresholding, i.e.binarizing the data based on the GLOBAL mean.

The SpatialRF model has a decent OOB R-squared and its other R-squared values are excellent. However, SpatialRF doesnt have functionality that supports prediction. Im looking to see if theres a way I can implement my own prediction function based on the output of SpatialRF.

Prediction with SpatialML

SpatialML, however, does include functionality for prediction, so Im giving that a shot next.

Predicting THY1 expression for sample 1

Next, I used this model to predict THY1 expression for the first dataset.

Statistical measures for accuracy

The SpatialML prediction function doesnt give any statistics relating to accuracy, and Ive seen a few different ways of measuring accuracy.

Linear Regression

Linear regression can give some insight into relation between actual and predicted THY1. Actual THY1 expression is not normal (heavily right skewed) so these results should be taken with a grain of salt

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = predicted_expression ~ THY1, data = with_predictions)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -36.432 -10.231  -0.864   9.243  61.180 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 20.32155    1.08892  18.662  < 2e-16 ***
## THY1         0.20617    0.03648   5.652 3.98e-08 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 14.14 on 274 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1044, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1011 
## F-statistic: 31.94 on 1 and 274 DF,  p-value: 3.978e-08

There is a linear relationship, however based on the THY1 coefficient, the predicted values are about 20% of what the actual THY1 values are.

Spearman Correlation

Another method of comparison is using Spearman Correlation. This was used in (this paper)[https://cancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/81/19/5115] which predicts bulk RNA expression from H&E slides.

## Warning in cor.test.default(with_predictions$THY1,
## with_predictions$predicted_expression, : Cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  with_predictions$THY1 and with_predictions$predicted_expression
## S = 2096488, p-value = 3.989e-12
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.4016958

The expression values ARE definitely correlated

Spatial patterns of accuracy

Next, I plotted THY1 expression. The second sample has higher overall THY1 expression, so it seems strange that running the model on the first sample would under-predict THY1 expression.

To further investigate, I looked at how accuracy of the model varied spatially.

The plot above shows the difference in THY1 expression (actual expression - predicted expression). There are clear spatial trends, with definitive areas that have high vs.low differences.

The above plot shows the absolute value of the difference, showing overall distance between actual and predicted expression. Light regions are less accurate (high difference between predicted and actual THY1 expression) and dark regions are more accurate (lower difference).
